    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-04T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-04T06:00:00-05:00" n="1034"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1034">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890D.01/5–445: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-04T13:00:00+02:00"
                            >May 4, 1945—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:32 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2343. Reurtel 1776, April 30. The Department’s views on the French decision to
                    send additional troops to the Levant States by warship were brought forcefully
                    to the attention of Chauvel<note n="84" xml:id="d1034fn84">Jean Chauvel,
                        Secretary of the French Ministry for Foreign Affairs.</note> who stated that
                    he was not in a position to give an official reply to my representations as this
                    question would have to be referred to General de <pb facs="1078" n="1066"
                        xml:id="pg_1066"/> Gaulle. He said that he assumed that I was familiar with
                    the representations made by Duff Cooper in this regard and the reply General de
                    Gaulle had made to him (reour tel 2315 to Department<note n="85"
                        xml:id="d1034fn85">May 3, <ref target="#pg_1064">p. 1064</ref>.</note> and
                    14 to Beirut). I replied in the affirmative and he said that he believed any
                    reply that might be forthcoming from de Gaulle would be in a similar vein.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 2343; repeated to Beirut 15.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
